note.p: A note seems to have been written in the margin next to this line but it is now illegible and partly lost.
Something beginning with "l" has been written in the right-hand margin but is mostly lost due to loss of writing surface.

There is virtually no sign of this line at the foot of fol. 1v or at the top of fol. 2r but it is present in a transcription by the Rev Alexander Cameron (Campbell and MacBain 1890-91: 248). He claims to have used this manuscript. His version of the line is therefore supplied here, on the assumption that it has been lost with a portion of the writing surface of either fol. 1 or fol. 2.

note.p: While there is an entry for this specific form in eDIL (s.v. duirge) the present editor understands it to a form of dúairc. This reading is supported by the following adjective with a similar sense and the form may have arisen from understanding duairc as a noun in this context with this form consequently being the attributive genitive, or, at some point during its transmission, the form may have been preceded by the plural fir.

When compared other versions of same poem in (e.g. The Book of O’Conor Don, f29v14), where the form dlaoi occurs at this location, dlith would not be an unusual rendering of the headword dlaí. Thus, although this specific instance of the word has its own eDIL entry (s.v. dlith), it is here tagged with the HW dlaí.

Black (HDSG slip 0040935) translates "don chollfhuil" as "of the chiefly blood". It is not clear if he understands "coll-" to refer to Colla Uais, legendary ancestor of Clann Domhnaill, or whether he is aware of a word, "coll", meaning literally "chiefly".

Other than Black's suggestion (HDSG Slip 0020438) that "áirseóir" had taken on the general sense of "hero", it is not clear why Eoin Mac Leoid should be referred to as "our archer". It is possible that this is in fact an otherwise unattested noun derived from "arsaidh", meaning "patriarch" or "ancestor" or suchlike.

Black (HDSG slip 0002290) seems to take this as an instance of "cúrsa" (course) but translates "at this time (?)". However, the verbal noun, "cur", can be used with the demonstrative pronoun, "so", to produce the same meaning idiomatically.
Black's translation (HDSG slip 0060078), "good likeness", is of the entire compound ("deaghcosmhuil"), not of the specified word ("cosmhuil").
The initial "g", which is unexpected in this context, has possibly been marked for deletion by surrounding puncta.
The "t-" has some unusual extra strokes and may have been scored out, perhaps suggesting that this is instead to be taken as a form of "oiret".

Black (HDDG Slip 0090200) suggests that "gineoil" is not a form of "cenél" but is instead a compound of "gein" (birth) and "eól" (knowledge), meaning "genealogy". However, the rhyme requires the second syllable to really be "-éil", so "cenél" must be the original reading.
Black (HDSG Slip 0110564) suggests that "aile" would be better read as "uile".
There is the trace of an n-stroke over the "a", now erased or eroded.
